{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569938"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:35:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:35:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22570"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22570"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.11,0.03,0.25,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15533"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110381"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15533"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22570"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92654"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4624"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"41659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110381"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit following intentional ingestion of 100 tablets of aspirin four hours ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears agitated. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Initial investigations reveal a serum salicylate level of 750 mg/L (therapeutic range 100-300). A venous blood gas was performed, with normal ranges as below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.35 - 7.45\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2: 35 - 45 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpO2: 80 - 100 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3-: 22 - 25 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBase excess: -2 to +2 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be seen on initial venous blood gas?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["pH 7.28, pCO2 45 mmHg, HCO3- 18 mmol/L, base excess -8 mmol/L","pH 7.48, pCO2 42 mmHg, HCO3- 28 mmol/L, base excess +5 mmol/L","pH 7.35, pCO2 40 mmHg, HCO3- 24 mmol/L, base excess 0 mmol/L","pH 7.52, pCO2 28 mmHg, HCO3- 22 mmol/L, base excess +1 mmol/L","pH 7.25, pCO2 25 mmHg, HCO3- 15 mmol/L, base excess -12 mmol/L"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute salicylate poisoning requiring intensive care admission. The initial phase of salicylate toxicity is characterised by direct stimulation of the respiratory centre in the medulla, leading to hyperventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.28, pCO2 45 mmHg, HCO3- 18 mmol/L, base excess -8 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents metabolic acidosis with inadequate respiratory compensation. This pattern develops later in salicylate toxicity as organic acids and lactate accumulate, but would not be the initial finding at four hours post-ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.48, pCO2 42 mmHg, HCO3- 28 mmol/L, base excess +5 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents metabolic alkalosis, which is not typically seen in salicylate poisoning. As toxicity progresses, patients develop metabolic acidosis rather than alkalosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.35, pCO2 40 mmHg, HCO3- 24 mmol/L, base excess 0 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents normal acid-base status, which would be unexpected in a patient with severe salicylate toxicity requiring intensive care admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.52, pCO2 28 mmHg, HCO3- 22 mmol/L, base excess +1 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents respiratory alkalosis, which is the earliest and most prominent acid-base disturbance, typically occurring within hours of ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.25, pCO2 25 mmHg, HCO3- 15 mmol/L, base excess -12 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents mixed respiratory alkalosis and metabolic acidosis, which can occur in later stages of severe salicylate poisoning but would not typically be seen at four hours post-ingestion in the initial phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of severe salicylate poisoning includes airway protection, correction of fluid and electrolyte abnormalities, and enhanced elimination through urinary alkalinisation or haemodialysis in severe cases. The decision to initiate renal replacement therapy is based on clinical severity, salicylate levels, and the presence of complications such as altered mental status or renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor further information on interpreting blood gases, refer to the case study: \u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/admin/cases/13561/16\u0022\u003EA medical student\u0027s guide to ABGs.\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aspirin toxicity initially causes respiratory alkalosis due to direct stimulation of the respiratory centre in the brain.","Later stages of aspirin toxicity lead to metabolic acidosis due to accumulation of organic acids and lactate.","Mixed acid-base disturbances are common in severe salicylate poisoning."],"references":["Runde TJ, Nappe TM. Salicylates Toxicity. [Updated 2023 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499879/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92654"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22570"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92654"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T16:14:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T16:15:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15533"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110381"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/687"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Drug overdose","synonyms":["Overdose","OD"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T15:27:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1061"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Fever","synonyms":["Pyrexia","Febrile","High temperature","Elevated temperature","Increased temperature","Fevers","Low-grade fever"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-06-11T11:13:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T13:18:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1569"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Venous blood gas","synonyms":["VBG"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2022-03-17T20:35:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-02T14:23:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"4"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2356"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc0d","name":"Toxicology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-06-06T01:28:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-06T01:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2706"},"